President Cyril Ramaphosa addressed the nation on Wednesday evening. JOHANNESBURG - President Cyril Ramaphosa admits racial tensions continue to open old wounds for South Africa. Ramaphosa has called for everyone to work towards bridging racism. READ: Ramaphosa urges men to do better in fight against GBV "What we have seen in Senekal and in Eldorado Park in Gauteng and in Brackenfell in Cape Town, shows that the state of race relations in our country remains fragile," he said. "We may have come a long way from the days of institutionalised racism but we are alive to the reality that for many reconciliation is something they have yet to experience." The president made the remarks during his annual Reconciliation Day speech.